  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Look at the function `take_or_turn()` in `custom.py`. It uses a `while` loop to move the `Painter` forward while it's facing east.\r\n\r\n   * Inside the loop, the `Painter` moves and checks if it's on a paint bucket.\r\n   \r\n   * If it *is* on a bucket, it takes all the paint.\r\n   \r\n   * But if it's **not** on a bucket, nothing happens!\r\n\r\n2. Add an `else` statement so the `Painter` turns right when it's *not* on a paint bucket.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/e025b324ee29d7dab8fd6c5c911729ac-choiceC.gif)\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nUse `else` to give the `Painter` a backup plan. Think of it as: *\"If not this, then that.\"*",
